Context
In the previous post we discussed this fantastic article (Moyer et al. 2019) which studied how different cleaning “interventions” applied to vacant lots had the potential to affect the propensity for nearby violent shootings. In this post we’ll look at the specific measures and statistical methods they used to analyze their data in order to test this hypothesis and break down the methods’ various advantages and disadvantages.
Methods
Data and Questions
Recall from the paper that the authors had shooting data accessed from the Philadelphia Police Department, and vacant lot data - location, size, and randomized intervention, that they amassed as part of their project. I’ve already shown, visually, what the shooting data looked like in the first post. As for the vacant lot data, it probably looked something like what’s in Table 1.


